● Completely fair question — and the honest answer is that this was a deliberate architectural choice made early in
   the project, not ignorance or missing tools.

  Why pure static HTML was chosen:

  The CLAUDE.md specifies:
  ▎ No build step, no dependencies — pure HTML/CSS/JS, open directly in a browser or served by Nginx.

  The reasoning at the time was simplicity for deployment: no Node.js, no npm, no build pipeline on the server —
  just files on disk that Nginx serves directly. That's a real advantage for a small personal site.

  What you're pointing at is the real cost of that choice:

  Any shared code (the nav script, the header, the footer) has to be copy-pasted into every file. When something
  needs changing — like today's logo fix — it means touching 109 files instead of 1.

  What the alternatives would look like:

  ┌─────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │            Approach             │         What you'd gain         │             What you'd add             │
  ├─────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Server-Side Includes            │ Single nav/header file          │ Nginx ngx_http_ssi_module must be      │
  │ (<!--#include-->)               │                                 │ enabled                                │
  ├─────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Plain JS fetch-and-inject       │ Single nav HTML file, fetched   │ A tiny JS snippet in every page (but   │
  │                                 │ at runtime                      │ identical)                             │
  ├─────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ 11ty / Hugo / Jekyll            │ Full templating, partials,      │ A build step; need Node/Go/Ruby on the │
  │                                 │ layouts                         │  server                                │
  ├─────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ React / Next.js                 │ Component model, hot reload,    │ Full JS framework, build pipeline,     │
  │                                 │ ecosystem                       │ much heavier                           │
  └─────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────┘

  My honest take:

  React would be overkill for a static diary site. But 11ty (Eleventy) or Hugo would be a natural fit — you'd write
   one layout template, one nav partial, and generate all 109 pages at build time. The output is still pure static
  HTML. The server wouldn't need to change at all.

  The JS fetch-and-inject approach is also attractive because it requires zero build tooling — you'd just have a
  nav.html partial that gets loaded into a <div id="site-top"> on page load.

  ---
  Worth raising: should the project migrate to a static site generator? It would eliminate this class of problem
  permanently. I'm happy to plan that out if you'd like.

  

